#key-point(title: [Sleep Spindle Deficits in ME/CFS])[
Sleep spindles are brief bursts of high-frequency brain activity (12–16 Hz) during non-REM sleep, essential for sleep stage transitions and CNS coordination. ME/CFS patients show reduced spindle density, correlating with cognitive dysfunction and non-restorative sleep quality (Chapter @sec:selective-dysfunction, lines 552–569).
]
